175:name: ai-coding-discipline
176:description: >
177:  Mandatory coding discipline rules that prevent common AI coding anti-patterns.
178:  MUST be loaded for ALL code writing, editing, reviewing, bug fixing, and testing tasks.
179:  Trigger on: writing code, editing code, fixing bugs, writing tests, implementing features,
180:  refactoring, code review, creating functions, adding error handling, debugging.
181:  This skill enforces fail-fast principles, proper error propagation, meaningful tests,
182:  and disciplined debugging workflows. Always active when Claude writes or modifies code.
183:---
184:
185:# AI Coding Discipline
186:
187:> These rules override default AI coding tendencies. Follow them in ALL code you write or modify.
188:
189:---
190:
191:## Rule 1: No Silent Fallbacks
192:
193:**Never use fallback values to mask data that should not be missing.**
194:
195:```typescript
196:// FORBIDDEN — hides upstream bugs
197:const price = product?.price ?? 0;
198:const userName = user?.name || "Unknown";
199:
200:// CORRECT — fail fast when data contract is violated
201:if (product.price == null) {
202:  throw new Error(`Product ${product.id} is missing price`);
203:}
204:const price = product.price;
205:```
206:
207:**When fallbacks ARE acceptable:**
208:- User-facing display with explicit design intent (e.g., avatar placeholder)
209:- Optional configuration with documented defaults
210:- External input parsing where absence is a valid state
211:
212:**Checklist before writing `??`, `||`, or `?.`:**
213:1. Can this value legitimately be null/undefined at this point?
214:2. If it is null, will the fallback produce a correct result downstream?
215:3. Would a thrown error help me find a bug faster?
216:
217:If the answer to #3 is yes, throw instead of falling back.
218:
219:---
220:
221:## Rule 2: No Catch-All try/catch in Business Logic
222:
223:**Business logic functions must NOT wrap everything in try/catch. Let errors propagate naturally.**
224:
225:```typescript
226:// FORBIDDEN — swallows all errors into a useless null
227:async function createOrder(data: OrderInput) {
228:  try {
229:    const user = await getUser(data.userId);
230:    const coupon = await validateCoupon(data.couponCode);
231:    const order = await saveOrder({ ...data, discount: coupon.value });
232:    return order;
233:  } catch (error) {
234:    console.log('Error creating order:', error);
235:    return null; // caller gets null, has no idea what failed
236:  }
237:}
238:
239:// CORRECT — let errors bubble up, catch at the boundary
240:async function createOrder(data: OrderInput) {
241:  const user = await getUser(data.userId);
242:  const coupon = await validateCoupon(data.couponCode);
243:  const order = await saveOrder({ ...data, discount: coupon.value });
244:  return order;
245:}
246:
247:// Catch ONLY at the API/controller boundary
248:app.post('/orders', async (req, res) => {
249:  try {
250:    const order = await createOrder(req.body);
251:    res.json(order);
252:  } catch (error) {
253:    logger.error('Order creation failed', { error, body: req.body });
254:    res.status(500).json({ error: 'Order creation failed' });
255:  }
256:});
257:```
258:
259:**Where try/catch IS appropriate:**
260:- API route handlers / controller boundaries
261:- Top-level event handlers (message queues, cron jobs)
262:- Operations where partial failure is expected and recovery is defined (e.g., batch processing with per-item error handling)
263:- Specific, named error types you intend to handle differently
264:
265:**Never catch `Error` just to return `null`, `undefined`, `false`, or an empty object.**
266:
267:---
268:
269:## Rule 3: Tests Must Fail When Code Breaks
270:
271:**Every test must verify specific business outcomes. A test that passes when the core logic is deleted is worthless.**
272:
273:```typescript
274:// FORBIDDEN — passes even if processOrder returns garbage
275:test('should process order', async () => {
276:  const result = await processOrder(mockOrder);
277:  expect(result).toBeDefined();
278:});
279:
280:// CORRECT — verifies exact business behavior
281:test('should calculate total with 10% discount', async () => {
282:  const result = await processOrder({
283:    ...mockOrder,
284:    discount: 0.1,
285:  });
286:  expect(result.totalAmount).toBe(900);       // 1000 * 0.9
287:  expect(result.discountAmount).toBe(100);
288:  expect(result.status).toBe('confirmed');
289:});
290:```
291:
292:**Test quality checklist:**
293:1. If I delete the function body, does this test fail? If not, the test is useless.
294:2. Am I testing behavior or just testing that "something exists"?
295:3. Do my assertions check concrete values, not just truthiness?
296:
297:**Banned weak assertions** (unless testing existence is the actual requirement):
298:- `toBeDefined()`, `toBeTruthy()`, `toBeFalsy()` as sole assertion
299:- `toHaveLength(expect.any(Number))`
300:- `expect(result).not.toBeNull()` without further value checks
301:
302:---
303:
304:## Rule 4: No Hardcoded Lookup-Table Implementations
305:
306:**Never implement business logic by hardcoding return values that match test cases.**
307:
308:```typescript
309:// FORBIDDEN — fake implementation that "fits" the tests
310:function calculateDiscount(amount: number, level: string): number {
311:  if (amount === 1000 && level === 'gold') return 100;
312:  if (amount === 500 && level === 'silver') return 25;
313:  return 0;
314:}
315:
316:// CORRECT — real logic
317:function calculateDiscount(amount: number, level: string): number {
318:  const rates: Record<string, number> = { gold: 0.1, silver: 0.05, bronze: 0.02 };
319:  const rate = rates[level] ?? 0;
320:  return amount * rate;
321:}
322:```
323:
324:**How to prevent this:**
325:- Use diverse test data: multiple amounts, edge cases, boundary values
326:- Add property-based / fuzzy tests where appropriate
327:- Test with values NOT in the original spec to catch lookup-table fakes
328:
329:---
330:
331:## Rule 5: Red-Green Testing (TDD Order)
332:
333:**When fixing a bug, always write the failing test FIRST, then fix the code.**
334:
335:```
336:Correct order:
337:1. Discover bug
338:2. Write a test that reproduces the bug
339:3. Run the test — confirm it FAILS (red)
340:4. Fix the code
341:5. Run the test — confirm it PASSES (green)
342:```
343:
344:**Why this matters:** If you fix the code first and then write a test, you can never be sure the test would have caught the bug. The test might pass for the wrong reason.
345:
346:**Never skip step 3.** Seeing the test go from red to green is the proof that the test is valid.
347:
348:---
349:
350:## Rule 6: Never Remove Debug Logs During a Fix
351:
352:**When debugging, debug logs are removed ONLY after the human confirms the fix works.**
353:
354:```
355:FORBIDDEN workflow:
356:1. Human asks to add debug logs
357:2. AI adds logs
358:3. Human runs code, shares log output
359:4. AI "finds the problem", applies fix AND removes debug logs in the same edit
360:5. Fix doesn't work — logs are gone, must re-add them
361:
362:CORRECT workflow:
363:1. Human asks to add debug logs
364:2. AI adds logs
365:3. Human runs code, shares log output
366:4. AI applies fix ONLY — debug logs stay untouched
367:5. Human verifies the fix
368:6. Human decides when to remove debug logs (or asks AI to remove them)
369:```
370:
371:**Rule: Never touch debug/diagnostic logs in the same commit as a fix. They are separate concerns.**
372:
373:---
374:
375:## Quick Reference: Self-Check Before Submitting Code
376:
377:Before finalizing any code change, run through this checklist:
378:
379:| Check | Question |
380:|-------|----------|
381:| Fallbacks | Did I use `??` or `\|\|` to hide a value that should never be missing? |
382:| Error handling | Did I add try/catch in business logic that should just let errors propagate? |
383:| Test strength | Would my tests still pass if I deleted the implementation? |
384:| Test honesty | Did I hardcode values to match test cases instead of implementing real logic? |
385:| TDD order | For bug fixes: did I see the test fail before applying the fix? |
386:| Debug logs | Am I removing diagnostic logs in the same change as the fix? |
387:
388:If any answer is "yes", revise before proceeding.
