490:| **L2** | 🛠️ Tool | Can I understand it next month? |
491:| **L3** | 🤝 Team | Can teammates take over? |
492:| **L4** | 🚀 Infra | Will others suffer if I break it? |
493:| **L5** | 🏛️ Critical | Can it pass audit? |
494:
495:---
496:
497:## Review Workflow
498:
499:Follow this sequence for every review:
500:
501:1. **Calibrate** — Ask Q1/Q2/Q3 → determine strictness level (or apply L3 fallback)
502:2. **Scope** — Confirm what to review: PR diff (changed files + immediate context), module, or specific files. If PR exceeds the level's size limit, flag it as an issue
503:3. **Language check** — Identify paradigm; read [language-adjustments.md](references/language-adjustments.md) if language is NOT Java/C#
504:4. **Review** — Walk through the 15-Point Checklist against the code
505:5. **Classify** — Assign severity to each finding (see Severity Classification below)
506:6. **Assess** — Add Effort/Benefit to Critical and Important issues
507:7. **Report** — Generate report using the template
508:8. **Verdict** — Apply verdict criteria to reach conclusion
509:
510:> **Review type adjustments:** For bug fixes, emphasize correctness and regression tests. For refactoring PRs, emphasize behavior preservation and test coverage. For new features, emphasize design and architecture. For test code, relax DRY tolerance.
511:
512:> **Priority order:** security > correctness > design > style. Rules serve the code, not vice versa.
513:
514:---
515:
516:## Strictness Matrix & Metric Thresholds
517:
518:**Quick reference:**
519:- Function length: L2(≤80) → L3(≤50) → L4(≤30) → L5(≤20)
520:- Parameter count: L2(≤7) → L3(≤5) → L4(≤3) → L5(≤2)
521:- Test coverage: L2(30%) → L3(60%) → L4(80%) → L5(95%)
522:
523:**For complete matrices:** See [positioning.md](references/positioning.md#strictness-matrix)
524:
525:### ⚠️ Measurement Rules (MUST follow)
526:
527:1. **Count logic lines only** — exclude docstrings, comments, blank lines
528:2. **Metrics are conversation starters, not hard gates**
529:3. **Do NOT report as issues (function length):**
530:   - Single-responsibility functions that cannot be meaningfully decomposed
531:   - Pure data builders, large switch/match statements, configuration mappings
532:   - A clear 60-line function beats three confusing 20-line functions *(exemption rationale, not default tolerance)*
533:4. **Do NOT report as issues (parameter count):** *(Pragmatic adjustment—original book has no explicit exemptions)*
534:   - Functions where most parameters have default values (count required params only)
535:   - Internal/private classes not directly instantiated by users
536:   - Configuration functions (e.g., `configure_logging(level="INFO", ...)`)
537:   - Factory/Builder patterns controlled by framework
538:5. **Do NOT report as issues (DRY/duplication):**
539:   - **DRY tolerance = max allowed repetitions.** Report when occurrences **exceed** this number:
540:     - L5: max 1 → report on 2nd occurrence
541:     - L4: max 2 → report on 3rd occurrence
542:     - L3: max 3 → report on 4th occurrence
543:     - L2: max 4 → report on 5th occurrence
544:     - L1: N/A (no limit)
545:   - **Accidental duplication** *(all levels)*: Similar code representing different business knowledge—do NOT report even if exceeds tolerance. Quick test: "If one changes, must the other ALWAYS change?" If no → accidental duplication → keep separate.
546:   - **Same file** *(L1-L3 only)*: Duplicates within same file are lower risk
547:   - See [principles-spectrum.md](references/principles-spectrum.md) for DRY vs WET guidance
548:
549:---
550:
551:## Language-Aware Review
552:
553:Before reviewing, identify the language paradigm:
554:
555:| Paradigm | Languages | Clean Code Applicability |
556:|----------|-----------|-------------------------|
557:| Pure OOP | Java, C# | ✅ Full |
558:| Multi-paradigm | TypeScript, Python, Kotlin | ⚠️ Adjust |
559:| Functional | Haskell, Elixir, F# | ⚠️ Many rules don't apply |
560:| Systems/Composition | Rust, Go | ⚠️ Different patterns |
561:
562:**For language-specific adjustments:** See [language-adjustments.md](references/language-adjustments.md)
563:
564:---
565:
566:## 15-Point Review Checklist
567:
568:### 1. Correctness & Functionality
569:
570:- [ ] **Logic implements requirements correctly?** (PP-75)
571:- [ ] **Boundary conditions and error handling complete?** (CC-153, PP-36)
572:- [ ] **Security vulnerabilities?** (PP-72, PP-73)
573:
574:### 2. Readability & Maintainability
575:
576:- [ ] **Names reveal intent?** (CC-4, PP-74)
577:- [ ] **Functions small and do one thing?** (CC-20, CC-21)
578:- [ ] **Comments explain "Why" not "What"?** (CC-39, CC-43)
579:
580:### 3. Design & Architecture
581:
582:- [ ] **Follows SRP?** (CA-8, CC-110)
583:- [ ] **Avoids duplication (DRY)?** (PP-15, CC-37)
584:- [ ] **Dependency direction correct?** (CA-12, CA-31)
585:
586:### 4. Testing
587:
588:- [ ] **New code has tests?** (PP-91, CC-194)
589:- [ ] **Tests readable and independent?** (CC-102, CC-106)
590:
591:### 5. Advanced Checks (L3+)
592:
593:- [ ] **Concurrency safe?** (PP-57, CC-137)
594:- [ ] **Security validated?** (PP-72, PP-73)
595:- [ ] **Resources released?** (PP-40)
596:- [ ] **Algorithm complexity appropriate?** (PP-63, PP-64)
597:
598:---
599:
600:## Common Code Smells
601:
602:| Smell | Rule | Quick Check |
603:|-------|------|-------------|
604:| Long function | CC-20 | Exceeds level threshold? (See Metric Thresholds + Measurement Rules) |
605:| Too many params | CC-26, CC-147 | Exceeds level threshold? (See Metric Thresholds + Measurement Rules) |
606:| Magic numbers | CC-175 | Unnamed constants? |
607:| Feature envy | CC-164 | Using other class's data? |
608:| God class | CC-109, CA-8 | Multiple responsibilities? |
609:| Train wreck | CC-81, PP-46 | `a.b().c().d()`? |
610:
611:**For full symptom lookup:** See [quick-lookup.md](references/quick-lookup.md)
612:
613:---
614:
615:## Red Flags - Investigate Further
616:
617:> ⚠️ **Language-aware:** Some red flags are paradigm-dependent. Always check [language-adjustments.md](references/language-adjustments.md) first.
618:
619:If you notice any of these, consult the reference files:
620:
621:- Switch statements (CC-24, CC-173) — *OOP only; match/when expressions are idiomatic in TS, Rust, Kotlin, FP languages*
622:- Null returns/passes (CC-92, CC-93)
623:- Commented-out code (CC-58, CC-144)
624:- Deep nesting (CC-22, CC-178)
625:- Global state (PP-47, PP-48)
626:- Inheritance > 2 levels (PP-51)
627:
628:---
629:
630:## DO NOT Review (Machine's Job)
631:
632:These should be caught by Linter/Formatter:
633:
634:- Formatting and indentation (CC-64~77)
635:- Basic naming conventions
636:- Unused variables/imports (CC-162)
637:- Basic syntax errors
638:- Missing semicolons/brackets
639:
640:**Focus on what machines can't:** Logic correctness, design decisions, architectural alignment.
641:
642:---
643:
644:## Severity Classification
645:
646:| Level | Criteria | Examples |
647:|-------|----------|---------|
648:| 🔴 **Critical** | Security vulnerabilities, data loss/corruption risks, logic bugs affecting correctness, crashes on production paths | SQL injection, unvalidated auth, off-by-one on financial calculation |
649:| 🟡 **Important** | Design principle violations, metric threshold breaches, maintainability risks, missing tests for critical paths | SRP violation, function with 10 params at L3, no test for core logic |
650:
651:**Rules:**
652:- Security issues are **always** Critical regardless of project level
653:- Severity is determined by the issue's *nature*, not by the effort to fix it
654:- Items below Important threshold are not reported — if an issue isn't worth actioning, omit it entirely
655:
656:---
657:
658:## Report Format
659:
660:> **Before reporting:** Apply Measurement Rules exemptions. Do NOT include exempt items (e.g., pure data builders exceeding line limits) in any issue category—omit them entirely.
661:
662:> **Empty sections:** If a severity tier has no issues, omit that section entirely from the report. Do not output a section header with "None" or "No issues found."
663:
664:> **Allowed sections only:** The report must contain exactly these sections: Critical Issues, Important Issues, Verdict. Do not add any other sections. Do not include praise, strengths, or positive observations anywhere in the report.
665:
666:```markdown
667:## 📋 Code Review Report
668:
669:**Project Positioning:** [Level] (e.g., L3 Team)
670:**Review Scope:** [files/commits reviewed]
671:
672:### 🔴 Critical Issues (Must Fix)
673:- **[file:line] Issue description**
674:  - Rule: XX-## (Rule Name)
675:  - Principle: Brief explanation of why this matters
676:  - Suggestion: How to fix it
677:  - Effort: [Low/Medium/High]
678:    - [reason derived from effort questions below]
679:  - Benefit: [Low/Medium/High]
680:    - [reason derived from benefit questions below]
681:
682:### 🟡 Important Issues (Should Fix)
683:- **[file:line] Issue description**
684:  - Rule: XX-## (Rule Name)
685:  - Principle: Brief explanation of why this matters
686:  - Suggestion: How to fix it
687:  - Effort: [Low/Medium/High]
688:    - [reason derived from effort questions below]
689:  - Benefit: [Low/Medium/High]
690:    - [reason derived from benefit questions below]
691:
692:---
693:
694:- **[file:line] Issue description**
695:  - Rule: XX-## (Rule Name)
696:  - Principle: Brief explanation of why this matters
697:  - Suggestion: How to fix it
698:  - Effort: [Low/Medium/High]
699:    - [reason derived from effort questions below]
700:  - Benefit: [Low/Medium/High]
701:    - [reason derived from benefit questions below]
702:
703:### 📝 Verdict
704:[✅ Ready to merge / ⚠️ Needs fixes / 🚫 Major rework needed]
705:```
706:
707:### Verdict Criteria
708:
709:> **Apply the first matching condition from top to bottom.**
710:
711:| Verdict | Condition |
712:|---------|-----------|
713:| 🚫 Major rework needed | ≥3 Critical issues OR fundamental design problems (dependency cycles, wrong architectural layer, framework-coupled domain logic) |
714:| ⚠️ Needs fixes | Any Critical issue OR >2 Important issues |
715:| ✅ Ready to merge | Zero Critical AND ≤2 Important issues |
716:
717:### Effort & Benefit (Critical/Important only)
718:
719:Add Effort and Benefit lines to each Critical and Important issue to help teams prioritize fix order. Each rating must include 1-3 nested bullet reasons derived from the questions below.
720:
721:- **Effort** — how hard to fix
722:  - Low: a few lines, < 30 min
723:  - Medium: moderate refactor, 30 min - 4 h
724:  - High: architectural change or wide-reaching modification, > 4 h
725:- **Benefit** — value gained after fixing (trigger frequency × impact scope)
726:  - High: hot path + severe consequence (data loss, security breach, outage)
727:  - Medium: common path + moderate impact, or edge case + severe consequence
728:  - Low: edge case + minor impact (UI glitch, degraded experience)
729:
730:**Before assigning ratings, reason through these questions:**
731:
732:For Effort:
733:- How many files need changes? (1 file = likely Low, 3+ files = likely Medium+)
734:- Does the fix cross module/layer boundaries? (yes = Medium+)
735:- Does existing test coverage need updating? (significant test changes = add one level)
736:
737:For Benefit:
738:- Is this code on a hot path (called frequently)? (yes = High trigger frequency)
739:- What's the worst-case consequence if this issue triggers? (data loss/security = High impact)
740:- Can users work around it? (no workaround = higher impact)
741:
742:If uncertain, default to the **more extreme** rating (Low or High), not Medium. Medium should be a deliberate choice, not a fallback.
743:
744:Express your reasoning as nested bullets under each rating line. Simple issues need 1 bullet; complex issues need 2-3 bullets. Reason bullets must derive from the questions above -- do not use generic justifications.
745:
746:### Report Example
747:
748:```markdown
749:## 📋 Code Review Report
750:
751:**Project Positioning:** L3 Team
752:**Review Scope:** src/services/user.ts, src/utils/helpers.ts
753:
754:### 🔴 Critical Issues (Must Fix)
755:- **[user.ts:45] SQL query built with string concatenation**
756:  - Rule: PP-72 (Keep It Simple and Minimize Attack Surfaces)
757:  - Principle: String concatenation in SQL queries creates injection vulnerabilities
758:  - Suggestion: Use parameterized queries: `db.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?', [userId])`
759:  - Effort: Low
760:    - Single file change, no cross-module impact
761:  - Benefit: High
762:    - Hot path -- every user query hits this code
763:    - Data loss/breach risk if exploited
764:
765:### 🟡 Important Issues (Should Fix)
766:- **[helpers.ts:120] Function `processUserData` has 8 parameters**
767:  - Rule: CC-26 (Function Arguments) + CC-147 (Too Many Arguments)
768:  - Principle: Many parameters increase cognitive load and make testing difficult. L3 threshold is ≤5.
769:  - Suggestion: Group related parameters into a `UserDataOptions` object
770:  - Effort: Medium
771:    - Touches callers across 3 files
772:    - Test updates needed for new signature
773:  - Benefit: Low
774:    - Internal utility, not on hot path
775:    - Users unaffected functionally
776:
777:---
778:
779:- **[user.ts:200] Duplicate validation logic (3rd occurrence)**
780:  - Rule: PP-15 (DRY) + CC-37 (Don't Repeat Yourself)
781:  - Principle: L3 allows max 3 repetitions. This is the 3rd occurrence -- consider extracting.
782:  - Suggestion: Extract to `validateUserInput(input)` function in utils
783:  - Effort: Low
784:    - Extract to shared function, update 3 call sites in same module
785:  - Benefit: Medium
786:    - Common path -- validation runs on every user mutation
787:    - Drift risk if logic diverges across copies
788:
789:### 📝 Verdict
790:⚠️ Needs fixes — Critical SQL injection issue must be addressed before merge
791:```
